📘 PHP Variables and Operators
-----------------------------
🔹 1. PHP Variables
A variable is a container for storing data (like numbers, strings, or arrays).


✅ Rules for Variables:
-----------------------
1) Must start with a $ sign.
2) Example: $name = "Ajay";
3) Must start with a letter or underscore _.
4) ❌ Not allowed: $9num = 10;
5) Can contain letters, numbers, and underscores.
6) Case-sensitive ($name and $Name are different).

✅ Declaring Variables:
<?php
$age = 25;          // Integer
$name = "Ajay";     // String
$price = 99.50;     // Float
$is_active = true;  // Boolean
?>

✅ Outputting Variables:
<?php
$name = "Ajay";
echo "Hello, my name is $name";   // Double quotes → variables are parsed
echo 'Hello, my name is $name';   // Single quotes → variables not parsed
?>



🔹 2. Variable Types in PHP
------------------------------
1) String → $name = "PHP";

2) Integer → $x = 100;

3) Float/Double → $pi = 3.14;

4) Boolean → $isValid = true;

5) Array → $colors = array("red","green","blue");

6) Object → Instances of classes

7) NULL → $var = null;

To know the type of variable we can use 

1️⃣ gettype()
<?php
$a = 42;
echo gettype($a);  // Outputs: integer
?>

2️⃣ var_dump()
<?php
$price = 19.99;
var_dump($price);
?>



==================================================================================
==================================================================================

🔹 3. Operators in PHP
Operators are symbols that perform operations on variables and values.
------------------------------------------------------------------------

✅ A) Arithmetic Operators
Used for mathematical calculations.

|Operator| Description         | Example  |
| ------ | ------------------- | -------- |
| +      | Addition            | $a + $b  |
| -      | Subtraction         | $a - $b  |
| *      | Multiplication      | $a * $b  |
| /      | Division            | $a / $b  |
| %      | Modulus (remainder) | $a % $b  |
| **     | Exponentiation      | $a ** $b |


<?php
$a = 10; $b = 3;
echo $a + $b; // 13
echo $a % $b; // 1
echo $a ** $b; // 1000
?>


==========================================================================================

✅ B) Assignment Operators
Used to assign values.

| Operator | Example    | Meaning       |
| -------- | ---------- | ------------- |
| `=`      | `$x = 10;` | Assign 10     |
| `+=`     | `$x += 5;` | `$x = $x + 5` |
| `-=`     | `$x -= 3;` | `$x = $x - 3` |
| `*=`     | `$x *= 2;` | `$x = $x * 2` |
| `/=`     | `$x /= 4;` | `$x = $x / 4` |
| `%=`     | `$x %= 2;` | `$x = $x % 2` |


==========================================================================================

✅ C) Comparison Operators
Used to compare values (returns true/false).


| Operator | Description                   | Example     |
| -------- | ----------------------------- | ----------- |
| `==`     | Equal                         | `$a == $b`  |
| `===`    | Identical (equal + same type) | `$a === $b` |
| `!=`     | Not equal                     | `$a != $b`  |
| `!==`    | Not identical                 | `$a !== $b` |
| `>`      | Greater than                  | `$a > $b`   |
| `<`      | Less than                     | `$a < $b`   |
| `>=`     | Greater than or equal         | `$a >= $b`  |
| `<=`     | Less than or equal            | `$a <= $b`  |
| `<=>`    | Spaceship (returns -1, 0, 1)  | `$a <=> $b` |

$a=10;
$b=10;

var_dump($a>$b);
==========================================================================================

✅ D) Logical Operators
Used to combine conditions.
=========================


<?php
$age = 20;
if($age >= 18 && $age <= 30){
    echo "Eligible";
}
?>
------------------------------------------------------------

<?php
$age = 16;
$has_permission = true;

if($age >= 18 || $has_permission){
    echo "Eligible";
} else {
    echo "Not Eligible";
}
?>


------------------------------------------------------------

<?php
$is_logged_in = false;

if(!$is_logged_in){
    echo "Please log in first!";
} else {
    echo "Welcome back!";
}
?>

==========================================================================================

✅ E) Increment/Decrement Operators
Used to increase/decrease a value.


| Operator | Description    | Example                      |
| -------- | -------------- | ---------------------------- |
| `++$x`   | Pre-increment  | Increment first, then return |
| `$x++`   | Post-increment | Return first, then increment |
| `--$x`   | Pre-decrement  | Decrement first, then return |
| `$x--`   | Post-decrement | Return first, then decrement |



==========================================================================================

✅ F) String Operators
Used with strings.

| Operator | Description   | Example    |
| -------- | ------------- | ---------- |
| `.`      | Concatenation | `$a . $b`  |
| `.=`     | Append        | `$a .= $b` |


<?php
$txt1 = "Hello";
$txt2 = " World!";
echo $txt1 . $txt2;   // Hello World!
?>


<?php
$a = "Hello";
$b = " World!";
$a .= $b;   // same as $a = $a . $b;
echo $a;
?>
o/p: Hello World!



